  "question": "Marissa is hiking a 12-mile trail. She took 1 hour to walk the first 4 miles, then another hour to walk the next two miles. If she wants her average speed to be 4 miles per hour, what speed (in miles per hour) does she need to walk the remaining distance?",
  "prompt": "Marissa is hiking a 12-mile trail. She took 1 hour to walk the first 4 miles, then another hour to walk the next two miles. If she wants her average speed to be 4 miles per hour, what speed (in miles per hour) does she need to walk the remaining distance?\n\nShow your work briefly and put the final answer in \\boxed{}.",
  "gold_answer": "6",
  "generated_text": "To find the required speed for the remaining distance, we need to determine the total time Marissa needs to complete the trail and the time already spent.\n\n**Step 1: Calculate the distance already walked.**\nMarissa walked the first 4 miles and then the next 2 miles.\n$$ \\text{Distance}_{\\text{walked}} = 4 \\text{ miles} + 2 \\text{ miles} = 6 \\text{ miles} $$\n\n**Step 2: Calculate the time already spent.**\nShe walked the first 6 miles in a total of 2 hours (1 hour for the first part + 1 hour for the second part).\n$$ \\text{Time}_{\\text{spent}} = 2 \\text{ hours} $$\n\n**Step 3: Calculate the remaining distance.**\nThe total trail length is 12 miles.\n$$ \\text{Distance}_{\\text{remaining}} = 12 \\text{ miles} - 6 \\text{ miles} = 6 \\text{ miles} $$\n\n**Step 4: Calculate the required average speed.**\nMarissa wants her average speed over the entire 12-mile trip to be 4 miles per hour.\n$$ \\text{Average Speed} = \\frac{\\text{Total Distance}}{\\text{Total Time}} $$\n$$ 4 = \\frac{12}{\\text{Total Time}} $$\n$$ \\text{Total Time} = \\frac{12}{4} = 3 \\text{ hours} $$\n\n**Step 5: Calculate the speed for the remaining distance.**\nThe remaining distance is 6 miles, and the total time allowed is 3 hours.\n$$ \\text{Speed}_{\\text{remaining}} = \\frac{\\text{Distance}_{\\text{remaining}}}{\\text{Time}_{\\text{remaining}}} $$\n$$ \\text{Speed}_{\\text{remaining}} = \\frac{6 \\text{ miles}}{3 \\text{ hours}} = 2 \\text{ mph} $$\n\nAlternatively, you can calculate the speed for the first part and subtract it from the target speed, but the direct calculation above is clearer.\nSpeed for first part: $4 \\text{ miles} / 2 \\text{ hours} = 2 \\text{ mph}$.\nTarget Speed: 4 mph.\nRemaining Speed needed: $4 - 2 = 2 \\text{ mph}$.\n\nBoth methods yield 2 mph.\n\n\\boxed{2}\n",
